  "text": "FISH analysis. Midguts from experimentally infected bees (n55) were carefully prepared and fixed in 4 % Histofix (Roth) overnight at 4 uC on a shaker. Fixed midguts were incubated in 6.8 % sucrose in PBS (pH 7.0) overnight at 4 uC followed by a dehydration step in 100 % acetone for 1 h at 4 uC with gentle agitation and a preinfiltration step in 50 % Technovit 8100/50 % acetone for 2 h at 4 uC on a shaker. Subsequently, the tissue was embedded in Technovit 8100 resin and blocked on Technovit 3040 resin (both Heraeus Kulzer) according to the manufacturer's instructions. The hybridization reaction was performed on histological sections (3-4 mm) essentially as previously described (Yue et al., 2008) . For the specific detection of DWV RNA via FISH the following 59-FITC-labelled oligonucleotides (Eurofinsdna) were used as probes [sequences according to GenBank accession no. AJ489744: 59-CCTGCTAAT-CAACAAGGACCTGG-39 (DWVF1-FITC) and 59-CAGAACCAAT-GTCTAACGCTAACCC-39 (DWVB1-FITC) ]. 59-Texas red-labelled probe EUK516 (59-ACCAGACTTGCCCTCC-39) [CITATION_1] was used to visualize the cytoplasm of honeybee cells via hybridization. Cellular nuclei were stained with 1 mg ml 21 DAPI in PBS for 10 min. Subsequently, the sections were washed three times with PBS, air-dried and mounted with ProLong Antifade reagent (Molecular Probes). Fluorescent microscopy was performed using a fluorescence microscope (Ti-Eclipse; Nikon) with a standard set of fluorescence filters.",
